.TH ACMEADDR 1
.SH NAME
acmeaddr \- print current selection address of an Acme window
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B acmeaddr
[
.I winid
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Acmeaddr
prints the current selection address of an
.MR acme 1
window to standard output:
the two rune offsets
.I q0
and
.I q1
(selection start and end), separated by a space.
.PP
It uses a single 9p connection to Acme: it writes
.B addr=dot
to the window's
.B ctl
file so that the window's
.B addr
file reflects the current dot (selection), then reads and prints
.IR addr .
This ensures the output matches the selection even when run from a script
invoked by
.B Run
in Acme.
.PP
.I Winid
is the Acme window id.
If omitted,
.I acmeaddr
uses the
.B $winid
environment variable, which Acme sets when you
.B Run
a command from a window's tag.
.SH EXAMPLE
From an Acme window tag, run a script that needs the current selection:
.IP
.EX
% acmeaddr
0 2048
.EE
.PP
With a selection in the body, the same command prints the rune range of the selection.
.SH SOURCE
.B \*9/src/cmd/acmeaddr.c
.SH SEE ALSO
.MR acme 1 ,
.MR acme 4
